5000|$|AO {{was first}} {{attempted}} for SLO in the 1980s. This first attempt {{did not use}} wavefront-detecting technology with its <b>deformable</b> <b>mirror</b> and estimated aberrations through pre-measured factors such as astigmatism. [...] However, this did not diffuse the small monochromatic aberrations resulting from light traveling through the anterior eye both {{into and out of}} the pupil during scanning. The invention and adaptation of the Shack-Hartmann wave-front detector for the apparatus produced images of the retina with much higher lateral resolution. [...] The addition of microelectricalmechanical (MEMs) mirrors instead of larger, more expensive mirror <b>deformable</b> <b>mirror</b> systems to the apparatus made AOSLO further usable for a wider range of studies and for use in patients.|$|E
